TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Social Processes of Organizational Sensemaking
AU  - Maitlis, Sally
Y1  - 2005/02/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2005.15993111
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2005.15993111
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 21
EP  - 49
VL  - 48
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A longitudinal study of the social processes of organizational sensemaking suggests that they unfold in four distinct forms: guided, fragmented, restricted, and minimal. These forms result from the degree to which leaders and stakeholders engage in ?sensegiving??attempts to influence others' understandings of an issue. Each of the four forms of organizational sensemaking is associated with a distinct set of process characteristics that capture the dominant pattern of interaction. They also each result in particular outcomes, specifically, the nature of the accounts and actions generated.
AB  - A longitudinal study of the social processes of organizational sensemaking suggests that they unfold in four distinct forms: guided, fragmented, restricted, and minimal. These forms result from the degree to which leaders and stakeholders engage in ?sensegiving??attempts to influence others' understandings of an issue. Each of the four forms of organizational sensemaking is associated with a distinct set of process characteristics that capture the dominant pattern of interaction. They also each result in particular outcomes, specifically, the nature of the accounts and actions generated.
